HW9

Interactive Visualization with Tableau

Q Liang



1 Data management

Create two subsets - county and state level elections results

1.1 County-level Data

  1. Calculate the percentage of each participating party within each county.
  2. Keep only the winning party in the data set
#Read data.
elections <- read.csv ("https://liangqs99.github.io/HW9/PresidentialElection2000To2020.csv",header=TRUE,sep=",")
#str(elections)
#head(elections)
#elections_year <- table(elections$year)
#elections_year
#elections_mode <- table(elections$mode)
#elections_mode
#num_var <- ncol(elections)
#num_var
#library(tidyverse)
#cleaning
#replaces candidate_votes by zero when it is missing
#replaces total_votes_county by the sum of votes in the county when it is missing.
elections_clean <- elections %>%
  group_by(year,state,county_fips) %>%
  mutate(candidatevotes = ifelse(is.na(candidatevotes), 0, candidatevotes),
         totalvotes = ifelse(is.na(totalvotes), sum(candidatevotes), totalvotes))
#Summarising the data so that the unit of observation is a candidate in a county
elections_clean <- elections_clean %>%
  group_by(year, state, state_po, county_name, county_fips, totalvotes, candidate, party) %>%
  summarise(all_votes = sum(candidatevotes)) %>%
  ungroup()
#Creating a variable pct_votes which is equal to the percentage of votes obtained by a candidate in a county
elections_clean <- elections_clean %>%
  mutate('pct_votes' = (all_votes/totalvotes)*100)
elections_clean$pct_votes<-format(round(elections_clean$pct_votes,1),nsmall=1)
#rank
elections_clean <- elections_clean %>%
  group_by(year, county_name, county_fips) %>%
  mutate('candidate_rank' = rank(desc(all_votes))) %>%
  ungroup()
#final county-level data
elections_county <- elections_clean %>%
  filter(candidate_rank == 1.0)
DT::datatable(elections_county, fillContainer = FALSE, options = list(pageLength = 10))


The above table shows the winner of presidential election in each county in US from 2000 to 2020. It also shows the total votes of every county, the winners votes and percentage.

In fact, its much easier to visualize the election results at county-level with Tableau even with the original data set.


1.2 State-level Data

  1. Calculate the percentage of each participating party within each state.
  2. Keep only the winning party in the data set
#Read data.
data0 <- read.csv ("https://liangqs99.github.io/HW9/PresidentialElection2000To2020.csv",header=TRUE,sep=",")

#library(tidyverse)
#cleaning
#replaces candidate_votes by zero when it is missing
#replaces total_votes_county by the sum of votes in the county when it is missing.
data1 <- data0 %>%
  group_by(year,state,county_fips) %>%
  mutate(candidatevotes = ifelse(is.na(candidatevotes), 0, candidatevotes),
         totalvotes = ifelse(is.na(totalvotes), sum(candidatevotes), totalvotes))
#remove NA rows (some state_po are NA)
data2 <- na.omit(data1)
#Summarising the data so that the unit of observation is a candidate in a state
data3 <- data2 %>%
  group_by(year, state, state_po, candidate, party) %>%
  summarise(all_votes = sum(candidatevotes)) %>%
  ungroup()
#Summarising the data to get the total in a state
data4 <- data3 %>%
  group_by(year, state) %>%
  summarise(total_votes = sum(all_votes)) %>%
  ungroup()
#join data2 and data3
data5 <- left_join(data3, data4)
#Creating a variable pct_votes which is equal to the percentage of votes obtained by a candidate in a state
data6 <- data5 %>%
  mutate('pct_votes' = (all_votes/total_votes)*100) 
data6$pct_votes <- format(round(data6$pct_votes,1),nsmall=1)
#rank
data7 <- data6 %>%
  group_by(year, state, state_po) %>%
  mutate('candidate_rank' = rank(desc(all_votes))) %>%
  ungroup()
#final county-level data
data8 <- data7 %>%
  filter(candidate_rank == 1)
#save it
#write.csv(data8, "/Users/qianshengliang/Dropbox/STA553/Week 10/elections_state.csv", row.names = FALSE)
DT::datatable(data8, fillContainer = FALSE, options = list(pageLength = 10))


The above table shows the winner of presidential election in each state in US from 2000 to 2020. It also shows the total votes of every state, the winners votes and percentage.

In fact, its much easier to visualize the state-level election results with Tableau even with the original data set.


2 Create an interactive choropleth map.

To display the presidential election results at the county level using two different colors to represent the two major parties.



The interactive map shows the US presidential election results at county-level from 2000 to 2020. It shows the winner (Republican: red, Democrat: blue) and other information in the hover text (winners name, party, year, state, county, votes, percentage, etc.).
